Bring a large #saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil for the potatoes.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} into 2cm chunks (peel first if you prefer).

When boiling, add the potatoes to the water and cook until you can easily slip a knife through, ~{15-20%minutes}.

In the meantime, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @green beans{80%grams} and cut them into thirds.

Strip the @thyme{1%bunch} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{240%grams} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Fry until golden brown on the outside and cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Halfway through cooking, add the green beans.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the thyme, garlic, @butter{10%grams} and @flour{10%grams} to the chicken. Cook, stirring frequently, for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @creme fraiche{75%grams}, @chicken stock paste{10%grams}, @wholegrain mustard{17%grams} and @water{150%ml} for the sauce.

Simmer the sauce until thickened slightly, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pan, off the heat. Add a knob of @butter{} and a splash of @?milk{} and mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

Just before you're ready to serve, stir the @honey{15%grams} through the sauce.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Add the @baby spinach{40%grams} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste the sauce and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of @?water{} if it's a little thick.

Spoon the mash onto one side of your #serving plates{}.

Serve your honey mustard chicken on the other half.

Enjoy!